    "optional_reagent_smiles": [
      "CS(C)=O",
      "C1CCN(CC1)C(=N)C1CCCCC1",
      "Cl.c1cc[nH+]cc1"
    ],
    "rationale": "This example shows the oxidation of a simple primary alcohol, 1-butanol, to the corresponding aldehyde, butanal. This is a classic textbook transformation for the Pfitzner-Moffatt oxidation. The reagents shown are dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO), dicyclohexylcarbodiimide (DCC), and pyridinium hydrochloride as the mild acid catalyst, which are the defining components of this reaction. The use of a simple, acyclic, aliphatic substrate avoids potential side reactions and focuses on the core functional group transformation.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "The substrate is a simple primary alcohol, avoiding complex structures, arenes, or other reactive functional groups that could overlap with other named reactions. The core transformation is a straightforward alcohol-to-aldehyde oxidation, which is specific to this class of reactions when these particular reagents (DMSO, carbodiimide, acid catalyst) are specified. This avoids collision with other oxidation reactions that use different reagents (e.g., Swern, Dess-Martin, PCC)."
  }
}
